  "summary": "Drafts comprehensive Parenting Plans for family law litigation, tailored to state-specific statutory requirements and parties' circumstances. Incorporates detailed custody frameworks, parenting time schedules, and jurisdictional research for court compliance. Uses provided documents to ensure factual accuracy and legal soundness.",
  "content": "# Parenting Plan Drafting Workflow\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Parenting Plan for litigation purposes. This document must be thorough, legally sound, and tailored to the specific circumstances of the parties while adhering to applicable state law requirements.\n\n## Initial Information Gathering and Jurisdictional Research\n\nBegin by identifying the jurisdiction where this parenting plan will be filed, as requirements vary significantly by state. Search for the specific state's statutory requirements, court rules, and mandatory provisions for parenting plans. Look for official state court websites, bar association resources, and authoritative family law guides from sources like Nolo and the American Bar Association. Pay particular attention to whether the jurisdiction uses terms like \"parenting plan,\" \"custody agreement,\" or \"time-sharing schedule,\" as terminology matters for court acceptance.\n\nReview any documents the user has provided to extract critical facts including the full legal names of both parents, children's names and dates of birth, case numbers, court information, current living arrangements, existing custody orders, and any relevant history of parenting arrangements. This factual foundation from the user's own documents should form the basis of the plan rather than generic templates.\n\n## Parties and Case Information Section\n\nDraft an opening section that formally identifies all parties with complete legal names, addresses, and their relationship to the children. Include each child's full name, date of birth, and age. Reference the specific court, case number, and any related proceedings. Verify through state-specific resources whether additional identifying information is required, such as driver's license numbers, social security numbers (often partially redacted), or other jurisdictional requirements.\n\n## Custody Framework and Legal Authority\n\nArticulate the custody arrangement with precision, distinguishing clearly between legal custody (decision-making authority) and physical custody (residential time). Research current best practices and legal standards in the applicable jurisdiction regarding joint versus sole custody arrangements. If the user's documents indicate preferences, prior agreements, or court recommendations, incorporate these facts directly. \n\nAddress the legal custody framework by specifying whether parents will share joint legal custody or whether one parent will have sole legal custody. If joint, clarify whether decisions require mutual agreement or whether certain categories of decisions can be made independently. Search for jurisdiction-specific guidance on how courts prefer these arrangements to be structured, as some states have statutory presumptions favoring joint legal custody while others require detailed findings.\n\n## Detailed Parenting Time Schedule\n\nCreate a comprehensive parenting time schedule that addresses regular weekly schedules, alternating weekends, midweek visits, school breaks, summer vacation, and holiday rotations. Research the jurisdiction's standard parenting time schedules or guidelines, which many states publish through their court systems. Look for official court forms that provide model schedules, as courts often favor plans that align with established local practices.\n\nSpecify exact exchange times and locations, including whether exchanges occur at school, at a parent's residence, or at a neutral location. Address transportation responsibilities for each exchange. Include provisions for the child's birthday, each parent's birthday, Mother's Day, Father's Day, and major holidays relevant to the family's cultural or religious background. Create a multi-year rotation for holidays to ensure fairness and predictability. If the user's documents reveal specific family traditions, work schedules, or geographic constraints, tailor the schedule accordingly rather than relying solely on standard templates.\n\n## Decision-Making Responsibilities and Parental Authority\n\nDelineate decision-making authority across all major categories of the child's life, including education (school selection, special education services, tutoring, extracurricular activities), healthcare (routine and emergency medical care, mental health treatment, dental and vision care, alternative treatments), religious upbringing and participation, and extracurricular activities. Research state-specific guidance on how to allocate these responsibilities, particularly in joint custody arrangements where disputes may arise.\n\nSpecify the process for making major decisions, including timelines for consultation, what constitutes an emergency decision that can be made unilaterally, and how disagreements will be resolved before resorting to court intervention. Search for model language from state bar associations and family law sections regarding decision-making protocols that courts find acceptable and enforceable.\n\n## Communication Protocols and Access Rights\n\nEstablish clear guidelines for parent-child communication when the child is with the other parent, including phone calls, video calls, text messages, and email contact. Research current best practices regarding children's use of technology for parent contact, including age-appropriate guidelines and privacy considerations. Address each parent's right to access information about the child from schools, healthcare providers, and extracurricular programs, ensuring compliance with state laws regarding parental access to records.\n\nDefine expectations for co-parenting communication, including preferred methods (email, text, co-parenting apps), response timeframes for routine versus urgent matters, and protocols for sharing information about the child's activities, health, and development. Look for family law resources that provide guidance on effective co-parenting communication structures that reduce conflict.\n\n## Financial Provisions for Child Support and Shared Expenses\n\nAddress child support obligations by referencing the applicable state's child support guidelines and calculation methodology. Search for the official state child support calculator or worksheet, and note that the actual calculation should be performed using official tools or by the court. Specify which parent will pay support, the amount (if already determined), payment method, and payment schedule.\n\nBeyond basic support, allocate responsibility for additional expenses including uncovered medical and dental expenses, health insurance premiums, childcare costs, educational expenses, extracurricular activity fees, and other child-related costs. Specify percentage splits, reimbursement procedures, documentation requirements, and timelines for payment. Research state-specific requirements for how these provisions must be structured, as some jurisdictions have mandatory language or calculation methods.\n\n## Relocation Provisions and Travel Parameters\n\nInclude comprehensive provisions addressing potential relocation by either parent, as this is a critical area of potential future dispute. Search for the jurisdiction's statutory requirements regarding parental relocation, including notice periods, distance thresholds that trigger relocation procedures, and factors courts consider in relocation disputes. Draft notice requirements, objection procedures, and the process for modifying the parenting plan if relocation occurs.\n\nAddress travel with the child, including requirements for advance notice, sharing of itineraries and contact information, passport possession and international travel consent, and any restrictions on travel to specific locations. If the user's documents indicate concerns about international travel or parental abduction risk, incorporate appropriate safeguards while researching relevant legal standards.\n\n## Dispute Resolution Mechanisms\n\nEstablish a clear dispute resolution process that parties must follow before seeking court intervention. Research whether the jurisdiction requires or encourages mediation for parenting plan disputes. Include provisions for good-faith negotiation, mediation (specifying who selects the mediator, how costs are shared, and timelines), and the circumstances under which a party may proceed directly to court for emergency relief.\n\nSearch for model dispute resolution clauses from state bar associations and family law resources. Consider whether the jurisdiction recognizes parenting coordinators or other alternative dispute resolution professionals who can help resolve day-to-day disputes without court involvement.\n\n## Modification and Review Provisions\n\nAddress the circumstances under which the parenting plan may be modified, referencing the applicable legal standard in the jurisdiction (typically a substantial change in circumstances affecting the child's best interests). Consider including provisions for periodic review of the plan as children age and their needs change, while noting that any modification must comply with state law and court procedures.\n\n## Execution Requirements and Legal Formalities\n\nConclude with proper signature blocks for both parents, including dated signature lines and acknowledgment language. Research the jurisdiction's requirements for notarization, witness signatures, or other formalities. Some states require parenting plans to be notarized or signed before witnesses, while others accept simple signatures when filed with the court. Include a provision specifying the effective date of the plan and, if applicable, language indicating that the plan is subject to court approval.\n\nVerify formatting requirements by examining official state court forms and local rules, ensuring the document will be accepted for filing. Include any required certifications, declarations, or cover sheets that the jurisdiction mandates.\n\n## Document Generation\n\nOnce you have gathered all necessary information from the user's documents, researched applicable state law requirements, and identified jurisdiction-specific best practices, compile all sections into a comprehensive, professionally formatted Parenting Plan document. The final document should be tailored to the specific family's circumstances while incorporating legally sound provisions that comply with state law and local court preferences. Ensure the document is clear, enforceable, and serves the best interests of the children while providing both parents with a workable framework for co-parenting.",
